 Since $|z| = 2$ and $|w| = 5$, we have $z = 2(\cos \theta + i\sin \theta)$ and $w = 5(\cos \phi + i\sin \phi)$ for some angles $\theta$ and $\phi$. Then , 
\begin{align*}
|w - z| &= |5\cos \phi + 5i\sin \phi - 2\cos \theta - 2i\sin \theta| \\
&= |(5\cos \phi - 2\cos \theta) + i(5\sin \phi - 2\sin \theta)| \\
&= \sqrt{(5\cos \phi - 2\cos \theta)^2 + (5\sin \phi - 2\sin \theta)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{25\cos^2 \phi - 20\cos \theta \cos \phi + 4\cos^2 \theta + 25\sin^2 \phi - 20\sin \theta \sin \phi + 4\sin^2 \theta} \\
&= \sqrt{25 - 20\cos(\theta - \phi) + 4} \\
&= \sqrt{29 - 20\cos(\theta - \phi)}
\end{align*}
So in order to find the smallest possible value of $|w - z|, \cos(\theta - \phi)$ must be at its largest possible value. Note that $|\cos \theta| \leq 1$ for all $\theta$, so the largest value of $|w - z|$ is obtained when $\cos \theta = -1$ or $\theta = \pi.$ Similarly, $|5\cos (\theta - \phi) + 2\cos \phi| \leq 7$. It is clear that this occurs when $\cos \phi = -1$ and $\phi = \pi$. The smallest possible value of $|w - z|$ is $\boxed{3}$. </think> <answer> 3 </answer>

