 Given two complex numbers, $z$ and $w$, we know that the magnitudes of both numbers are 2 and 5, respectively. This means (\textit{for example}: $z=2i$ and $w=5$). According to the triangle inequality for complex numbers, one of the following scenarios must be true:
\begin{align}
|w| = |z| + |w-z| \quad &\implies  5 = 2+|w-z| \\
|w| =|z| - |w-z| \quad &\implies  5 = 2-|w-z| \\
|w| \pm |z| = |w-z|  && \text{ (The cases above are exclusive)} 
\end{align}
The first and second scenarios give $\; |w-z| = 3\;$  and $\; |w-z| = 7\;$, respectively, while the second scenario yields a contradiction. The smallest possible value for $|w - z|$ among the values we get is $\boxed{3}$.</think><answer> $3$</answer>

